{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_adamsmorgan_ver01/data/sn84026749/00222254668/1929122601/1388.xml":{"full_text":"MARKET OFFERS\nPOST-HOLIDAY\nBARGAINS.\nBy MERRYLE 8. RUKEYSER\n(Copyright, IMS, -by Universal\nr ___ Service, Inr.)\nTF Wall Street pursued modem\nmerchandising methods, it\n1 too' would focus attention on\npost-holiday bargains.\nPublic apathy, tax selling,\ntesting out of vulnerable spots\nby short sellers, professional\ndislike of gold exports and\ntemporary firming up of money\nrates, and skepticism over the\nshort term business outlook\nhave gradually effaced most of\nthe gains registered in the\npost-panic rally.\nA Accordingly, the common\nstock purchasing power of the\ndollar has again risen. Left\novers, remnants and even\nstand-patters at the security\nposts are available not only\nat prices which/are cheap in\ncomparison with bull market\npeaks, but also in more sens!-\nb ble terms of known earnings,\nactual assets and probable fu\nture prospects.\nThe ticker reflects the pre\nvailing mood, and the discern-\nIng. analytical long term in\nvestor has traditionally found\nit safer to make commitments\nin times of pessimism rather\nthan on occasions of overflow\ning public optimism.\nIrrespective of the short term\noutlook for common stock\nprices, the advice to buy bonds\nis still timely. After the turn\nof the year, seasonal factors\nshould tend further to ease in-\ntgrest rates, and lay the eco-\nnomic setting for a further ad\nvance in high-grade bond\nprices. High coupon European\ngovernment bonds should also\nparticipate in the revival es\npecially if international bank\ners are serious about making\nan offer to investors of repara\ntion bonds.\nV\nThe public has learned in re\ncent months that even the best\nstocks may be uhattractive, if\nt priced unwarrantably high.\nHa\u2019ving analyzed the behavior\nof stock prices over an extend\ned period, Karl Karsten, the\nNew Haven statistician, has\nfound, however, that the best\ngrade of stocks do not sink in\na bear market relatively as far\nas the worst grade. The mid\ndle grade of stocks, he says, are\nmore sluggish on both the up\nand down side than either of\nthe extreme classes. He said:\n\"Not all companies within\nan industrial group share\nalike in the fortunes of the\nr Industry, In any representa\ntive cross-section several stocks\nV will be found which climb fas\nter than the aggregate during\nprosperous periods and sag'\nless during depressed periods.\nSuch companies present un\nusual opportunity for invest-'\nment, and could they be con\ntinued in time, our funds\nwould mount faster than if\na spread over the aggregate.\n\"The selection of intrinsically\nI good stocks, and reliance upon\ntheir intrinsic quality to pro-\nduce long-term investment\nprofit is a high type of modern\nInvestment procedure.\n\"The actual future price\nmovement of any one stock,\nhowever, is not due wholly to\nqualities of management, earn\ning capacity, nor to strategic\nposition. Such qualities raise\nor lower the stock above or be\nlow the level of its competi\ntors. But the best company in\nan industry will suffer when\nthe industry wanes, and in\nmany cases purely industrial\nconditions will sweep a com-\nparatively poor stock up the\nprice range in the race of a\nbull movement.\n\"Obviously, therefore, a good\nstock in ar prospering industry\nis better than a good stock in\na waning industry. Or, from\ni another viewpoint, a good stock\nmay be temporarily a poor buy,\nIf the industry upon which it\ndepends be entering -upon a\ndull period.\"\nImmediately after the late\ndebacle in Wall Street, the\neconomic sages at Harvard\nUniversity expressed the view\nthat nothing worse than a\nshort business recession lay\nahead. But they pointed out\nthat their opinion was provi\nsional, pending the receipt of\ns further data. Now, viewing the\nr situation from a better per\nspective, they forecast a recov\nv ery of business next spring,\n\"with further improvement in\nthe fall, so that 1930, as a\nwhole, should prove at least\na fairly good year.\u2019*\nSummarizing the status of\nbusiness, the Harvard Economic\nSociety, in its current survey,\nsays:\n\u201cThe figures show that the\nbusiness recession already un\nder way became decidedly\nworse after the crash, but did\nnot go to such lengths as to\nIndicate disaster. The severest\ndeclines occurred ,in physical\noutput (notably of automobiles\nand of such baric goods as\nIron, steel, non-ferrous metals,\ntextiles, and the like) and were\nquickly reflected in smaller\nfreight movement.\nThe canvenlenea at Timo ar Herald\nCtaaaMied \u00bbd\u00bb to doubly realiaed If ymi I\nWtototo dnrtag th. ranked h*a-\n\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014a H mmuiwassm\u00ab\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0ugriK\nWashington Times r inancial News\nCOMPLETE TRANSACTIONS ON NEW YORK CURB.MARKET\nQuotations Fernisbed by W. B. Hibba A Co.\nOta ng#\nlit\u201d Name A44 M RKi U# Hill\n31\u2018* 7 Aero 1nd....;.... 1 7>. 7H 7M\nm Aera Supply 1 10 10 10\n48H 14H Aero Underwear., ft VH W/6 14Jf T H\n43M J 5 Afga Anae0.,,.4.. 10 It 18 It -IM\nJOM 3 Air Investors 0 3H 3H 3H\n23 IM Alesander 1nd.... 1/ 2k 2 2- M\n110* 23 Allied FA U 18 34 31H 34 4- IM\n52 40k Allied FA Lt Vtu. 7 4M 40 45\n22M 5h A\u00ae MfH ACont... 14 fH 5M \u00a3H +M\n00k 10 Am Wise Pow B. 39 UH 14k 14H\n31M 18 Am Comnw A 14 24!. 24h 24k\nIlk 2k Am Comnw Pww. 2 3 3 8 k\nM Am Conlr 0H..... 3 Ji k k\n69k 20k Am L'yaa b 5 20 25k 25k** k\n29 3H AmDept Btoro.. M 12 3k 3k 3k**\n33k 15 Am Equities. .31 10k Uk l-\u2019H- k\n17l 15k Am FPw ww 18 01 59k <1 2\n224\u20194 70 AaauABI.. M 10 115 114 115\n42k fl \u201e4m inv ins 20 9M 9\u2019> 9k- Ik\n399 190 Ana Lt a T....... 1 218 218 218 4* 8\n8. 1k Am Maracaibo.. 5 Ik, Ik Ik\n71Ji 15 Am Hup p0w..... to 23k 22 <3H+ Ik\nICOJi 85k Am Mup Pow Ist p: 3 t>sk 95k 9M+ H\n25k 8 An Poet Fence N. 1 14 14 14 4* M\n18 11 Anglo Am cod..\u2022\u2022 37 Ilk 16k 10k- k\n09 55 Apponsug........ 1 ttH IBk \u00a3.B+4\u2014 k\n15k 9k Arctur